geo:siteIdentification.geo:notes: The site is in an area of early Miocene (Waitemata group) sandstone and mudstone strata with occasional volcaniclastic debris flows (Parnell grit). The strata are superficially folded. Basement is Jurassic greywacke at about 200-300 m depth. Monument construction. A hole was augered through clayey soil to refusal at about 1.2 m depth in compact sediments, and was widened at the bottom by spade. A small amount of concrete was placed at the bottom, then a 2.4 m long by 30 cm O.D. concrete tube was placed vertically in the hole. Three or four lengths of reinforcing bar bent over at their bottom end were placed inside the yube. Concrete was poured to fill the hole external to the tube, and the inside of the tube. A 15 cm diameter stainless plate with protruding 5/8"-11 screw was set exactly horizontal in the top of the concrete. Height of pillar above pad is 1.27 m to top corner of pillar, 1.28 m to the level of the stainless plate. The top concrete surface of the pillar was deliberately made uneven to reduce resonance effects between the top of the pillar and the antenna. The surface of the stainless plate serves as the height reference point.

geo:siteLocation.geo:notes: Located at the NZ MetService automatic weather station in the grounds of the Whangaparaoa Army/ Navy Camp. Approx 1 hr drive north of Auckland. Communication is by phone.

geo:GnssReceiver.geo:notes: A receiver with choke-ring antenna was run at a temporary site a few metres from AUCK for two days before and after the exchange of the AUCK receiver and antenna. The data will be used to determine whether there is any apparent position offset associated with the exchange.
Galileo, BeiDou and QZSS enabled with this firmware upgrade.

geo:HumiditySensor.geo:notes: The height difference to antenna accuracy is +- 2 m. Met sensors are at the NZ MetService automatic weather station, and predate the installation of the GPS receiver. The sensors are calibrated annually by NZ MetService. Start and end date don't reflect the effective one, which are unknown. For any further required info please contact NZ MetService.

Met sensors are runned by NZ MetService. Sensors are co-located to the site, but not connected to the GNSS receiver. Combined Humidity and Air Temperature sensor. Antenna to height difference accuracy is +- 2 m.
